  langid      = {english},
  abstract    = {We estimate the causal effects of occupational delicensing on firm performance and management in the Chinese insurance industry. Using individual-level data from a major life insurance company and a sharp regression discontinuity design, we show that agents hired after the reform earn 75.2% lower first-month commissions, exhibit a 12.5% higher 12-month turnover rate, and are 12.0% less likely to be promoted. Difference-in-differences estimates reveal performance declines among incumbents (36.0%) and managers (44.0%), with spillovers through team-based compensation. Despite the workforce expansion and demographic shifts, aggregate commissions fall by 11.3%. Delicensing harms firm outcomes contrary to the reform's stated objectives.},
